[[Atheism]] and [[agnosticism]] have a long history in India and flourished within the [[Śramaṇa|Sramana movement]]. Indian religions like [[Jainism]], [[Buddhism]] and certain schools of [[Hinduism]], though not all, consider atheism to be acceptable.<ref name="wayoflife"/><ref name="Joshi"/> India has produced some notable atheist politicians and [[reform movement|social reform]]ers.<ref name="secularism"/> According to [[2011 Census of India]], 99.76% of Indians identified with a religion while 0.24% did not state their religious identity.<ref name="census_2011_religion">{{cite web |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-01/DDW00C-01%20MDDS.XLS |title=Population by religious community - 2011 |publisher=Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner |work=[[2011 Census of India]] |accessdate=25 August 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825155850/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-01/DDW00C-01%20MDDS.XLS |archivedate=25 August 2015}} Percentages are calculated from population figures for individual religions in this word document by dividing them from total population of India.</ref><ref name=census2011>{{cite web|title=All India Religion Census Data 2011|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/religion.php|publisher=[[Government of India]]|accessdate=1 March 2011}}</ref> According to the 2012 WIN-Gallup Global Index of Religion and Atheism report, 81% of Indians were religious, 13% were non-religious, 3% were convinced atheists, and 3% were unsure or did not respond.<ref name=gallup2012>{{cite web|title=Global Index Of Religion And Atheism |url=http://redcresearch.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/RED-C-press-release-Religion-and-Atheism-25-7-12.pdf |publisher=WIN-Gallup |accessdate=3 September 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016062403/http://redcresearch.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/RED-C-press-release-Religion-and-Atheism-25-7-12.pdf |archivedate=16 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>

== History ==

===Ancient India===
{{See also|Śramaṇa}}

====Schools of Philosophy====
{{See also|Indian philosophy}}
In Hinduism, the religion of the majority of [[India]]ns, [[atheism]] is considered to be a valid path to [[spirituality]], as it can be argued that God can manifest in several forms with "no form" being one of them. But, the path is considered difficult to follow.<ref name="wayoflife">{{Cite book | last = Chakravarti| first = Sitansu| title = Hinduism, a way of life| publisher = Motilal Banarsidass Publ.| year = 1991| page = 71| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=J_-rASTgw8wC&pg=PA71| isbn = 978-81-208-0899-7| accessdate=2011-04-09}}
</ref> The belief in a personal creator God is not required in [[Jainism]] and [[Buddhism]], both of which also originated in the Indian subcontinent. [[Atheism in Hinduism|Atheistic schools]] are also found in Hinduism.<ref name="Joshi">{{cite journal |last=Joshi |first=L.R. |year=1966 |title= A New Interpretation of Indian Atheism |journal=Philosophy East and West |volume=16 |issue=3/4 |pages=189–206|doi= 10.2307/1397540 |publisher=University of Hawai'i Press |jstor=1397540}}</ref>

[[Hindu philosophy]] is divided into schools (''darśanam''). These schools can be categorised as ''āstika'' (orthodox), schools which conforms to the [[Vedas]], and ''nāstika'' (heterodox), schools reject the Vedas. The six schools ''[[Sāṃkhya]]'', ''[[Yoga]]'', ''[[Nyāya]]'', ''[[Vaiśeṣika]]'', ''[[Mimāṃsā]]'' and ''[[Vedānta]]'' are considered ''āstika'' (orthodox), while [[Jainism]], [[Buddhism]], ''[[Cārvāka]]'' and [[Ājīvika]] are considered  ''nāstika'' (heterodox).<ref name="nastika">{{cite book|author=Y. Masih|title=A Comparative Study of Religions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8E-DSnG_8KYC&pg=PA157|accessdate=7 September 2013|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-0815-7|page=157}}</ref>

=====Cārvāka=====
{{Main|Cārvāka}}
{{Rquote|right|There is no heaven, no final liberation, nor any soul in another world, Nor do the actions of the four castes, orders, etc., produce any real effect.|from the '' Sarvadarśanasaṅ̇graha'', attributed to ''Brhaspati''<ref>{{cite book|author=Ramkrishna Bhattacharya|title=Studies on the Carvaka/Lokayata|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=59eygxzQTWQC&pg=PA91|accessdate=8 September 2013|year=2011|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-0-85728-433-4|pages=91}}</ref><ref name="Madhava">{{cite book|author=Mādhava|title=The Sarva-darśana-saṃgraha|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/34125/34125-h/34125-h.htm|accessdate=8 September 2013|year=1908|publisher=Project Gutenberg}}</ref>}}

The ''Cārvāka'' school originated in India around the 6th century BCE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/Not-scared-of-God-but-man/articleshow/46570208.cms|title=Not scared of God, but man}}</ref> It is classified as a ''[[nāstika]]'' school. It is noteworthy as evidence of a [[Materialism|materialistic]] movement in ancient India.<ref name=moor>{{cite book|author1=Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan|author2= Charles A. Moore|title= A Sourcebook in Indian Philosophy|publisher=Princeton University Press| year=1957|edition= Twelfth Princeton Paperback printing 1989| pages= 227–249|isbn= 0-691-01958-4}}</ref> Followers of this school only accepted ''pratyakşa'' (perception) as a valid ''pramāna'' (evidence). They considered other ''pramāna'' like ''sabda'' (testimony), ''upamāna'' (analogy), and ''anumāna'' (inference) as unreliable.<ref name="pramana">{{cite book|author=Deepak Sarma|title=Classical Indian Philosophy: A Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5TK5I6R9xtkC&pg=PA4|accessdate=7 September 2013|year=2011|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-13399-9|pages=4–}}</ref> Thus, the existence of a soul (''ātman'') and God were rejected, because they could not be proved by perception. They also considered everything to be made of four [[Mahābhūta|elements]]: earth, water, air and fire. The Cārvāka pursued elimination of physical pain and enjoyment of life. So, they can be considered [[hedonistic]].<ref name="hedonism">{{cite book|author=Eugene F. Bales|title=A Ready Reference to Philosophy East and West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=34cjS0M1rFIC&pg=PA211|accessdate=7 September 2013|year=1987|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0-8191-6640-1|pages=211–}}</ref> All of the original Cārvāka texts are considered lost.<ref name="carvakalost">{{cite book|author=William M. Indich|title=Consciousness in Advaita Vedanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ykZjWOiBMoC&pg=PA35|accessdate=7 September 2013|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-1251-2|pages=35–}}</ref> A much quoted ''[[sūtra]]'' ([[Barhaspatya sutras]]) by Brhaspati, who is considered the founder of the school, is thought to be lost.<ref>{{cite book|author=Eugene F. Bales|title=A Ready Reference to Philosophy East and West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=34cjS0M1rFIC&pg=PA211|accessdate=7 September 2013|year=1987|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0-8191-6640-1|pages=211}}</ref> The ''Tattvopaplavasimha'' by [[Jayarāśi Bhaṭṭa]] (8th century CE) and the ''Sarvadarśanasaṅ̇graha'' by [[Madhavacarya]] (14th century) are considered important secondary Cārvāka texts.<ref name="hedonism"/>

=====Sāṃkhya=====
{{Main|Sāṃkhya}}
''Sāṃkhya'' is an ''āstika'' school, but has some atheistic elements. Sāṃkhya is a radically [[dualism (Indian philosophy)|dualist]] philosophy.<ref name="dual">{{cite book|author=Richard King|title=Indian Philosophy: An Introduction to Hindu and Buddhist Thought|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uca8R72W8iQC&pg=PA63|accessdate=7 September 2013|year=1999|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-0-7486-0954-3|pages=52, 63}}</ref> They believed that the two [[ontology|ontological principles]], ''puruṣa'' (consciousness) and ''prakriti'' (matter), to be the underlying foundation of the universe.<ref name="dual"/><ref name="Dasgupta">{{cite book|author=Surendranath Dasgupta|title=A History of Indian Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PoaMFmS1_lEC&pg=PA238|accessdate=7 September 2013|year=1992|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-0412-8|page=238}}</ref> The objective of life is considered the achievement of separation of pure consciousness from matter (''[[kaivalya]]'').<ref name=dual/> The reasoning within this system led to the ''Nir-isvara Sāṃkhya'' (''Sāṃkhya'' without God) philosophy, which deemed the existence of God as unnecessary.<ref name="nir-isavara">{{cite book|author=Dale Maurice Riepe|title=Naturalistic Tradition in Indian Thought|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UZZGEhp8gasC&pg=PA210|accessdate=7 September 2013|date=1 December 1996|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-1293-2|page=210}}</ref> There is the opposing reasoning which accepts God, called ''Sesvara Sankhya'' (''Sāṃkhya'' with God).<ref name="withgod">{{cite book|author=Andrew J. Nicholson |title=[[Unifying Hinduism: Philosophy and Identity in Indian Intellectual History]] |url=|publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=978-0-231-52642-5|pages=118–}}</ref> ''[[Samkhya Karika]]'' (c. 350 CE) is the earliest known systematic text of this philosophy.<ref name=dual/>

=====Mīmāṃsā=====
{{Main|Mīmāṃsā}}
''[[Mīmāṃsā]]'' (meaning [[exegesis]])<ref name=dual/> is also an ''astika'' school. They believed the Vedas to be author-less and self-authenticating.  They did not accept the Vedas as being composed by any ''[[ṛishi]]'' (saint), they considered them to not be authored by anyone (''apauruṣeya''). They accepted the minor deities of the Vedas but resisted any notion of a Supreme Creator. They only concentrated on upholding the ''[[ṛta]]'' (order) by following the duties of the Vedas. The foundational text of this school is the ''Mīmāṃsā Sutra'' by [[Jaimini]] (c. 200 BCE - 200 CE).<ref name=dual/>

=====Ājīvika=====
{{Main|Ājīvika}}
''[[Ājīvika]]'' is yet another ''astika'' school with an atheistic outlook. None of their scriptures survive and there is some question as to whether or not the accounts of them in secondary sources (often hostile) are accurate. They believed in a naturalistic atomic theory and held that the consequence of natural laws led to a deterministic universe. They denied [[karma]], but upheld the [[Ātman (Hinduism)|atman]]. They lived in ascetic communities and existed in southern India until at least the 14th century.

=====Buddhism and Jainism=====
{{See also|God in Buddhism|God in Jainism}}
[[Gautama Buddha]] rejected the existence of a [[Creator deity#Buddhism|creator deity]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Thera|first=Nyanaponika|title=Buddhism and the God-idea|url=http://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/nyanaponika/godidea.html|work=The Vision of the Dhamma|publisher=Buddhist Publication Society|location=Kandy, Sri Lanka|quote=In Buddhist literature, the belief in a creator god (issara-nimmana-vada) is frequently mentioned and rejected, along with other causes wrongly adduced to explain the origin of the world; as, for instance, world-soul, time, nature, etc. God-belief, however, is placed in the same category as those morally destructive wrong views which deny the kammic results of action, assume a fortuitous origin of man and nature, or teach absolute determinism. These views are said to be altogether pernicious, having definite bad results due to their effect on ethical conduct.}}</ref><ref>''Approaching the Dhamma: Buddhist Texts and Practices in South and Southeast Asia'' by Anne M. Blackburn (editor), Jeffrey Samuels (editor). Pariyatti Publishing: 2003 {{ISBN|1-928706-19-3}} pg 129</ref> refused to endorse many views on creation<ref>{{cite book|title=The All Embracing Net of Views: Brahmajala Sutta|year=2007|publisher=Buddhist Publication Society|url=http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/dn/dn.01.0.bodh.html|author=Bhikku Bodhi|editor=Access To Insight|location=Kandy, Sri Lanka|chapter=III.1, III.2, III.5}}</ref> and stated that questions on the origin of the world are not ultimately useful for ending [[dukkha|suffering]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Acintita Sutta: Unconjecturable|url=http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/an/an04/an04.077.than.html|work=AN 4.77|publisher=Access To Insight|author=Thanissaro Bhikku|language=English|year=1997|quote=Conjecture about [the origin, etc., of] the world is an unconjecturable that is not to be conjectured about, that would bring madness & vexation to anyone who conjectured about it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cula-Malunkyovada Sutta: The Shorter Instructions to Malunkya|url=http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/mn/mn.063.than.html|publisher=Access To Insight|author=Thanissaro Bhikku|language=English|year=1998|quote=It's just as if a man were wounded with an arrow thickly smeared with poison. His friends & companions, kinsmen & relatives would provide him with a surgeon, and the man would say, 'I won't have this arrow removed until I know whether the man who wounded me was a noble warrior, a priest, a merchant, or a worker.' He would say, 'I won't have this arrow removed until I know the given name & clan name of the man who wounded me... until I know whether he was tall, medium, or short... The man would die and those things would still remain unknown to him. In the same way, if anyone were to say, 'I won't live the holy life under the Blessed One as long as he does not declare to me that 'The cosmos is eternal,'... or that 'After death a Tathagata neither exists nor does not exist,' the man would die and those things would still remain undeclared by the Tathagata.}}</ref> [[Buddhism]] instead emphasises the system of causal relationships underlying the universe, [[pratītyasamutpāda]], which constitute the [[dharma]] and source of enlightenment. No dependence of phenomena on a supernatural reality is asserted in order to explain the behaviour of matter.

[[Jainism]] rejects the idea of a [[creator deity]] responsible for the manifestation, creation, or maintenance of this universe. According to Jain doctrine, the universe and its constituents (soul, matter, space, time, and principles of motion) have [[Jainism and non-creationism|always existed]]. All the constituents and actions are governed by universal natural laws and an immaterial entity like God cannot create a material entity like the universe. Jainism offers an elaborate [[Jain cosmology|cosmology]], including heavenly beings (devas), but these beings are not viewed as creators; they are subject to suffering and change like all other living beings, and must eventually die. Jains define godliness as the inherent quality of any soul characterising infinite bliss, infinite power, [[Kevala Jnana]] (pure infinite knowledge){{sfn|Sangave|2001|p=164}} and Perfect peace. However, these qualities of a soul are subdued due to [[Karma in Jainism|karmas]] of the soul. One who achieves this state of soul through [[Ratnatraya|right belief, right knowledge and right conduct]] can be termed a god. This perfection of soul is called kevalin or [[bodhi]]. A god thus becomes a liberated soul – liberated of miseries, cycles of rebirth, world, karmas and finally liberated of body as well. This is called [[Moksha (Jainism)|moksha]].

====Philosophers and ancient texts====
[[Ajita Kesakambali]] was a [[materialist]] philosopher. He is mentioned in the ''[[Samaññaphala Sutta]]''. He rejected gods, an afterlife and karma.<ref name="ajita kesa">{{cite book|author=David J. Kalupahana|title=Ethics in Early Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sXhp8w6r93QC&pg=PA16|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=1 January 2008|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publishe|isbn=978-81-208-3280-0|pages=16–17}}</ref> [[Payasi]] is a character, referred to as a prince, who appears in the Buddhist text ''[[Digha Nikaya]]'' in the ''Payasi Sutta''. He didn't believe in rebirth or karma. He debated [[Mahākāśyapa|Kassapa]], a disciple of Buddha, and lost according to Buddhist sources.<ref name="payasi2">{{cite book|author=K. R. Norman|title=Pāli Literature: Including the Canonical Literature in Prakrit and Sanskrit of All the Hīnayāna Schools of Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XdCkFokTBbEC&pg=PA40|accessdate=9 September 2013|year=1983|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=978-3-447-02285-9|page=40}}</ref><ref name="IndianPhilo">{{cite book|author=Surendranath Dasgupta|title=A History of Indian Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PoaMFmS1_lEC&pg=PA106|accessdate=7 September 2013|year=1992|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-0412-8|page=106}}</ref>

=====Jabali's speech from the Ramayana=====
{{See also|Jabali}}

In the Hindu epic ''[[Ramayana]]'' (''Ayodhya Khanda''), when [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharata]] goes to the forest to convince [[Rama]] to return home, he was accompanied by a [[sophist]]<ref name="jabali sophist">{{cite book|title=A Comparative History of Ideas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gpulmza7BBYC&pg=PA152|accessdate=9 September 2013|year=1992|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=978-81-208-1004-4|page=152}}</ref> called [[Jabali]] ("{{lang|sa|जाबालिः}}"). Jabali uses [[nihilism|nihilistic]]<ref name="nihilist jabali"/> reasoning to convince Rama. He also says that rituals are a waste of food and scriptures were written by smart men so that people will give alms. But Rama calls him a deviant from the path of ''[[dharma]]'' ("{{lang|sa|धर्मपथात्}}"), refuses to accept his "''nastika''" views and blame his own father for taking Jabali into service.<ref name=valmiki_uncensored>{{cite book|title=Ramayana|page=Sarga 108–109|author=Valmiki|authorlink=Valmiki|chapter=Ayodhya Kanda}}</ref> He also equates the Buddha to a thief.<ref name=valmiki_uncensored/> On hearing Rama's retort, Jabali retracts his statements, saying that he was merely arguing like a nihilist.<ref name="nihilist jabali">{{cite book|title=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jvkAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA307|accessdate=9 September 2013|year=1862|publisher=Cambridge University Press for the Royal Asiatic Society|page=307}}</ref> However, these verses referring to the Buddha<ref name="buddha jabali">{{cite book|author=Mahadev Moreshwar Kunte|title=The Vicissitudes of Âryan Civilization in India: An Essay, which Treats of the History of the Vedic and Buddhistic Polities, Explaining Their Origin, Prosperity, and Decline|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YzIQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA449|accessdate=9 September 2013|year=1880|publisher=printed at the Oriental Printing Press by N. W. Ghumre|page=449}}</ref> are considered a later [[Interpolation (manuscripts)|interpolation]], as those verses use a different [[Metre (poetry)|metre]].<ref name="buddha jabali"/><ref name="directed at buddhist?">{{cite book|author=Sanujit Ghose|title=Legend of Ram: Antiquity to Janmabhumi Debate|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rfgkCrumMfYC&pg=PA140|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Bibliophile South Asia|isbn=978-81-85002-33-0|pages=140}}</ref>

=====The Carvaka incident in the Mahabharata=====
A character described as a Carvaka briefly appears in the ''[[Mahabharata]]'' (in the ''[[Shanti Parva]]''). As [[Yudhishthira]] enters the city of [[Hastinapur]], a [[brahmin]], referred to as Carvaka, accuses him of killing his own kinsmen and says that he would suffer for it. The accuser is revealed to a ''[[rakshasa]]'' in disguise, who was a friend of [[Duryodhana]]. He had existed since the [[Krita Yuga]] by virtue of a boon from the god [[Brahma]], that he could only be killed when he is showing contempt towards brahmins. He was killed by other brahmins by the chanting of sacred hymns and Yudhishthira was assured that his actions were the within the [[kshatriya]] code.<ref name="Fitzgerald">{{cite book|author=James L. Fitzgerald|title=The Mahabharata, Volume 7: Book 11: The Book of the Women Book 12: The Book of Peace|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8iIbqXwKoxIC&pg=PA86|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=15 February 2003|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-25250-6|pages=255–258}}</ref> This event may be a possible denigration of the [[Carvaka]] philosophy.<ref name="carvaka maha">{{cite book|author=Arvind Sharma|title=Essays on the Mahābhārata|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KnCxH85Vra4C&pg=PA309|accessdate=9 September 2013|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publishe|isbn=978-81-208-2738-7|pages=309–}}</ref>

===Medieval India===
In the 9th century CE, Jain philosopher Jinasena wrote the [[Mahapurana (Jainism)|Mahapurana]]. The book contains the following often quoted words,<ref name="world">{{cite book|author=Warren Matthews|title=World Religions, 7th ed.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3V4zalTcXCwC&pg=PA156|accessdate=8 September 2013|date=22 December 2011|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-111-83472-2|page=156}}</ref>

{{Cquote|Some foolish men declare that a creator made the world. The doctrine that the world was created is ill-advised, and should be rejected. If god created the world, where was he before creation? If you say he was transcendent then, and needed no support, where is he now?}}

This quote was also featured later in [[Carl Sagan]]'s book, [[Cosmos (book)|Cosmos]].<ref name="Cosmos">{{cite book|author=Carl Sagan|authorlink=Carl Sagan|title=Cosmos|year=1985|publisher=Ballantine Books|isbn=978-0-345-33135-9|chapter=Chapter 10}}</ref> In the 14th century, philosopher Madhavacarya wrote the ''Sarvadarśanasaṅ̇graha'', which is a compilation of all Indian philosophies, including ''Carvaka'', which is described in the first chapter.<ref name="Madhava"/>

=== Modern India ===

====19th century====

Between 1882 and 1888, the Madras Secular Society published a magazine called ''The Thinker'' (''Tattuvavivesini'' in [[Tamil language|Tamil]]) from [[Madras]]. The magazine carried articles written by anonymous writers and republished articles from the journal of the London Secular Society, which the Madras Secular Society considered itself affiliated to.<ref name="madras journal">{{cite news|title=Tracing the history of an unknown radical group|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/tracing-the-history-of-an-unknown-radical-group/article5203705.ece?homepage=true|accessdate=7 October 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=5 October 2013}}</ref>

====20th century====
[[File:YUKTHIVADI.JPG|thumb|align=left|150px|The [[Yukthivadi]] in 1929 was the first [[atheist]]/[[rationalist]] magazine published in [[Malayalam]].]] 
[[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy]] (1879 - 1973) was an atheist and rationalist leader of [[Self-Respect Movement]] and [[Dravidar Kazhagam]]. His views on the irreligion are based on the eradication of the caste system, religion must be denied to achieve the obliteration of caste system.

[[Vinayak Damodar Savarkar]] (1883 –1966) was an eminent [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] leader of the [[Indian independence movement]]. He was also an atheist and a staunch [[rationalist]]<ref>{{Cite book|title = Towards Understanding Communalism|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=8_RtAAAAMAAJ|publisher = Centre for Research in Rural and Industrial Development|date = 1992-01-01|isbn = 9788185835174|first = Pramod|last = Kumar}}</ref> who disapproved of orthodox [[Hindu]] belief, dismissing [[Cattle in religion|cow worship]] as superstitious.<ref>{{Cite news|title = The man who thought Gandhi a sissy|url = https://www.economist.com/news/christmas-specials/21636599-controversial-mentor-hindu-right-man-who-thought-gandhi-sissy|newspaper = The Economist|access-date = 2016-01-23|issn = 0013-0613}}</ref> Being Hindu, for him, was a cultural and political identity.

[[Satyendra Nath Bose]] (1894 – 1974) was an atheist [[physicist]] specialising in [[mathematical physics]]. He is best known for his work on [[quantum mechanics]] in the early 1920s, providing the foundation for [[Bose–Einstein statistics]] and the theory of the [[Bose–Einstein condensate]].

[[Meghnad Saha]] (1893 – 1956) was an atheist [[astrophysicist]] best known for his development of the [[Saha equation]], used to describe chemical and physical conditions in stars.

[[Jawaharlal Nehru]] (1889–1964), India's first [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] was a self-described [[scientific humanist]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Sankar Ghose|title=Jawaharlal Nehru, a Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MUeyUhVGIDMC&pg=PA332|accessdate=30 September 2013|year=1993|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=978-81-7023-369-5|page=332}}</ref> He wrote in his [[autobiography]], ''[[Toward Freedom]]'' (1936), about his views on religion and superstition.<ref name="voices">{{cite book|author=Dale McGowan|title=Voices of Unbelief: Documents from Atheists and Agnostics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wWWU32YNq4UC&pg=PA139|accessdate=8 September 2013|date=7 September 2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-978-3|page=139}}</ref>

[[Bhagat Singh]] (1907-1931), an Indian revolutionary and socialist nationalist who was hanged for using violence against British government officials. He laid out his view in the essay [[Why I Am an Atheist]], written in jail shortly before his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/715660/on-bhagat-singhs-death-anniversary-why-i-am-an-atheist|title=On Bhagat Singh's death anniversary: 'Why I am an atheist'}}</ref>

[[Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar]] (1910–1995), atheist [[astrophysicist]] known for his theoretical work on the structure and [[evolution of stars]]. He was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] in 1983.

[[Goparaju Ramachandra Rao]] (1902-1975), better known by his [[nickname]] "Gora", was a social reformer, anti-caste activist and atheist. He and his wife, [[Saraswathi Gora]] (1912-2007) who was also an atheist and social reformer, founded the [[Atheist Centre]] in 1940.<ref name="humanism">{{cite book|author=Wiel Veugelers|title=Education and Humanism: Linking Autonomy and Humanity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T_4Wyzz-utoC&pg=PA114|accessdate=8 September 2013|date=16 November 2011|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-94-6091-577-2|page=114}}</ref> The Atheist Centre is an institute working for social change.<ref name="Disenchanting India">{{cite book|author=[[Johannes Quack]]|title=Disenchanting India: Organized Rationalism and Criticism of Religion in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TNbxUwhS5RUC&pg=PA338|accessdate=12 August 2013|date=22 November 2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-981260-8|pages=89, 338}}</ref> Gora expounded his philosophy of [[positive atheism]] as a way of life.<ref name=humanism/>  He later wrote more about positive atheism in his 1972 book, ''Positive Atheism''.<ref name="gorapositive">{{cite book|author=Robyn E. Lebron|title=Searching for Spiritual Unity...Can There Be Common Ground?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KILFE33zGngC&pg=PA532|accessdate=8 September 2013|date=January 2012|publisher=CrossBooks|isbn=978-1-4627-1262-5|page=532}}</ref> Gora also organised the first World Atheist Conference in 1972. Subsequently, the Atheist Centre has organised several World Atheist Conferences in [[Vijayawada]] and other locations.<ref name="Disenchanting India"/>

[[Khushwant Singh]] (1915-2014), a prominent and prolific writer, of Sikh extraction, was avowedly non-religious.

In 1997, the [[Federation of Indian Rationalist Associations]] was founded.<ref name=atheism_voice>{{cite news|title=In India, atheism finds its voice|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/1197562/report-in-india-atheism-finds-its-voice|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=DNA India|date=13 October 2008}}</ref>

====21st century====

[[Amartya Sen]] (1933-), an Indian [[economist]], philosopher and [[List of Nobel laureates|Nobel laureate]], is an atheist<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Arguing Indian|url = http://alumni.berkeley.edu/california-magazine/july-august-2006-indo-chic/arguing-indian|website = Cal Alumni Association|access-date = 2016-01-23}}</ref> and he holds that this can be associated with one of the [[Atheism in Hinduism|atheist schools]] in [[Hinduism]], the [[Charvaka|Lokayata]].<ref>{{Cite news|title = A World Not Neatly Divided|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/23/opinion/a-world-not-neatly-divided.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2001-11-23|access-date = 2016-01-23|issn = 0362-4331|first = Amartya|last = Sen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = News & Broadcast - Amartya Sen Speaks on Culture at World Bank|url = http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/NEWS/0,,contentMDK:20045541~pagePK:64257043~piPK:437376~theSitePK:4607,00.html|website = web.worldbank.org|access-date = 2016-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Rediff On The NeT Business News: Market economy not the panacea, says Sen|url = http://www.rediff.com/business/1998/dec/28sen.htm|website = www.rediff.com|access-date = 2016-01-23}}</ref>

[[Maharashtra Rationalist Association | Mumbai Rationalist Association]], the successor of Maharashtra Rationalist Association<ref>{{cite book|last=Quack|first=Johannes|date= 2012|title=Disenchanting India: Organized Rationalism and Criticism of Religion in India|url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199812608.001.0001/acprof-9780199812608-chapter-10|location= |publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=101-106|isbn=9780199812608}}
</ref>, is actively involved in developing scientific temper and eradicating superstition.   

In 2008, the website Nirmukta was founded. It later became an organisation aiming to promote [[free thought]] and [[secular humanism]] in India.<ref name="milliongods" />

In 2009, historian [[Meera Nanda]] published a book entitled "The God Market". It examines how Hindu religiosity is gaining more popularity in the rising [[middle class]], as India is liberalising the economy and adopting [[globalisation]].<ref name=glitter>{{cite news|title=The Glitter In The Godliness|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?263657|accessdate=6 September 2013|newspaper=[[Outlook India]]|author=William Dalrymple|authorlink=William Dalrymple (historian)|date=18 January 2010}}</ref>

In March 2009, in [[Kerala]], a [[pastoral letter]] addressing the [[laity]] was issued by the [[Kerala Catholic Bishops' Council]] urging the members to not vote for political parties which advocate atheism.<ref name="don't vote">{{cite news|title=Don’t vote for those who preach atheism: Kerala church body|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/don-t-vote-for-those-who-preach-atheism-kerala-church-body/438276/|accessdate=2 October 2013|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=24 March 2009}}</ref><ref name="don't vote2">{{cite news|title=Kerala Church makes a poll sermon|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-others/tp-states/kerala-church-makes-a-poll-sermon/article1049087.ece?ref=archive|accessdate=2 October 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindu Business Line]]|date=12 April 2009}}</ref> In July 2010, another similar letter was issued.<ref name="don't vote 2010">{{cite news|title=Church blow to ‘atheist’ parties|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100726/jsp/nation/story_12726907.jsp|accessdate=2 October 2013|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)]]|date=26 July 2010}}</ref>

On 10 March 2012, [[Sanal Edamaruku]] investigated a so-called miracle in [[Vile Parle]], where a [[Jesus]] statue had started weeping and concluded that the problem was caused by faulty drainage. Later that day, during a TV discussion with some church members, Edamaruku accused the [[Catholic Church]] of miracle-mongering. On 10 April, Angelo Fernandes, President of the Maharashtra Christian Youth Forum, filed a police complaint against Edamaruku under the [[Hate speech laws in India|Indian Penal Code Section 295A]].<ref name=jesus>{{cite news|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/article/2/2012041720120417220221187efd41360/FIR-against-rationalist-for-questioning-%E2%80%98miracle%E2%80%99.html|title=FIR against rationalist for questioning ‘miracle’|date=17 April 2012|newspaper=Mumbai Mirror|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615170321/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/article/2/2012041720120417220221187efd41360/FIR-against-rationalist-for-questioning-%E2%80%98miracle%E2%80%99.html|archivedate=15 June 2012|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref> In July while on a tour in [[Finland]], Edamaruku was informed by a friend that his house was visited by the police. Since the offence is not [[bail]]able, Edamaruku stayed in Finland.<ref name=jesus2>{{cite news|title=Jesus wept … oh, it's bad plumbing. Indian rationalist targets 'miracles'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/nov/23/india-blasphemy-jesus-tears|accessdate=6 September 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=23 November 2012}}</ref>

On Friday 7 July 2013, the first "Hug an Atheist Day" was organised in India by Nirmukta. The event aimed to spread awareness and reduce the stigma associated with being an atheist.<ref name=hug>{{cite news|title=Think free and hug an atheist this Friday|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/1844423/report-think-free-and-hug-an-atheist-this-friday|accessdate=8 September 2013|newspaper=[[DNA India]]|date=6 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=hug2>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Give-the-atheist-closest-to-you-a-hug/2013/06/06/article1621383.ece?pageNumber=1&parentId=77669&operation=complaint|title=Give the atheist closest to you a hug|accessdate=8 September 2013|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=6 June 2013}}</ref>

On 20 August 2013, [[Narendra Dabholkar]], a rationalist and anti-superstition campaigner,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/govind-pansare-mm-kalburgi-gauri-lankesh-murder-5316465/|title=Indian rationalism, Charvaka to Narendra Dabholkar}}</ref> was shot dead by two unknown assailants, while he was out on a morning walk.<ref name=dabholkar>{{cite news|title=Rationalist Dabholkar shot dead|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/rationalist-dabholkar-shot-dead/article5041138.ece|accessdate=6 September 2013|newspaper=The Hindu|date=20 August 2013}}</ref>

There is a growing number of Indian Muslims gradually leaving Islam, driven by a questioning mind and joining the group of Ex-Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/indias-ex-muslims-shedding-traditional-islam-for-science-3093252.html|title=India's ex-Muslims: Shedding traditional Islam for science}}</ref>

==Legal status, rights and laws==

Atheism and irreligion are not officially recognised in India. [[Apostasy]] is allowed under the right to [[Freedom of religion in India|freedom of religion]] in the [[Constitution of India|Constitution]], and the [[Special Marriage Act, 1954]] allows the marriage of people with no religious beliefs, as well as non-religious and non-ritualistic marriages. However, there are no specific laws catering to atheists and they are considered as belonging to the religion of their birth for administrative purposes.<ref name=milliongods>{{cite news|title=Indian atheists seek recognition in the land of a million gods|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-30/science/32483706_1_atheists-religion-beliefs|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=30 June 2012}}</ref>

===Hate speech laws and irreligion===
{{Main|Hate speech laws in India}}

===Notable verdicts===

On 29 October 2013, the [[Bombay High Court]] judged in favour of an atheist school teacher from [[Nashik]].<ref name="atheist teacher">{{cite news|title=Teacher cannot be forced to fold hands in school prayers: Bombay high court|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Teacher-cannot-be-forced-to-fold-hands-in-school-prayers-Bombay-high-court/articleshow/25137023.cms|accessdate=4 November 2013|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=2 November 2013}}</ref> Sanjay Salve had been employed by the state-funded Savitribai Phule Secondary School since 1996. In June 2007, during a prayer session, Salve didn't fold his hands during the pledge or prayer. The school management called this indiscipline and refused him a higher pay grade in 2008 when Salve became eligible for it. Salve sought legal recourse citing the Section 28 (a) of the Constitution which states "no person attending any educational institution recognised by the State or receiving aid out of State funds shall be required to take part in any religious instruction that may be imparted in such institution or to attend any religious worship that may be conducted in such institution".<ref>{{cite law|title=Constitution of India, Section 28 (a)|date=1950}}</ref><ref name="what wrong">{{cite news|title=Pray, what wrong did I do, asks atheist teacher|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/pray-what-wrong-did-i-do-asks-atheist-teacher/article5080102.ece?ref=relatedNews|accessdate=4 November 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=20 September 2013}}</ref> The court ruled in Salve's favour and directed the school to release his dues by 31 January 2013.<ref name="answers prayers">{{cite news|title=Bombay High Court answers atheist teacher's prayer; asks school to pay dues|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-bombay-high-court-answers-atheist-teacher-s-prayer-asks-school-to-pay-dues-1911611|accessdate=4 November 2013|newspaper=[[DNA India]]|date=31 October 2013}}</ref>

On 23 September 2014, the [[Bombay High Court]] declared that the government cannot force a person to state a religion on any document or form. The court also stated any citizen has the right to declare that he/she doesn't belong to any religion. The decision came in response to a [[Public Interest Litigation]] (PIL) filed by Ranjit Mohite, Kishore Nazare and Subhash Ranware, representing an organisation called Full Gospel Church of God, after the Maharashtra state printing press refused to issue them a gazette notification stating that they belonged to no religion. The petitioners stated that the organisation had 4000 members, and that they believe in [[Jesus Christ]] but they do not follow [[Christianity]] or any religion. Responding to the petition, the Maharashtra and the central governments had stated that "no religion" cannot be treated as a religion on official forms. The court cited the Article 25 of the Constitution, which guarantees right to freedom of conscience,  while passing the verdict.<ref name=no_religion_BHC>{{cite news|title=Citizen can declare that he does not belong to any religion: Bombay High Court|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/citizen-can-declare-that-he-does-not-belong-to-any-religion-bombay-high-court/1/392828.html|accessdate=26 November 2014|work=[[India Today]]|date=26 Sep 2014}}</ref><ref name=BHC_religion>{{cite news|title=Citizen can declare that he does not belong to any religion: Bombay High Court|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/citizen-can-declare-that-he-does-not-belong-to-any-religion-bombay-high-court/|accessdate=26 November 2014|work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=24 Sep 2014}}</ref>

==Persecution and attacks==
{{see also|Persecution of atheists}}
[[Narendra Nayak]] has claimed to have been attacked thrice and twice had his scooter damaged, one of the attacks leaving him with head injuries. This compelled him to take self-defence lessons and carry a [[nunchaku]].<ref name=nunchaku1>{{cite news|title=Rationalists fight superstition with dignity and nunchakus|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-08-22/bangalore/41435861_1_karnataka-superstition-karate|accessdate=6 September 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=22 August 2013}}</ref> [[Tarksheel Society|Megh Raj Mitter]]'s house was surrounded by a mob after he debunked the [[Hindu milk miracle]], forcing him to call the police.<ref name=Twilight>{{cite news|title=Confrontation in the Twilight zone|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/beyond-business/confrontation-in-the-twilight-zone-113083001107_1.html|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=Business Standard|date=30 August 2013}}</ref>

On 15 March 2007, a bounty of {{currency|7|INR}} [[lakh]] was announced on atheist<ref name=Theocracy>{{cite news|title=Taslima on IBNLive chat: 'India is not a theocracy'|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/taslima-on-ibnlive-chat-india-is-not-a-theocracy/56692-7-9.html|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=[[IBNLive]]|date=18 January 2008}}</ref> [[Bangladesh]]i author [[Taslima Nasrin]], while living in India, by a [[Muslim]] cleric named Maulana Tauqeer Raza Khan for allegedly writing derogatory statements about Mohammad in her work.<ref name=TaslimaHead>{{cite news|title=Muslim body announces Rs 5 lakh for Taslima's head|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-muslim-body-announces-rs-5-lakh-for-taslimas-head-1085098|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=[[DNA India]]|date=15 March 2007}}</ref> In December 2013, an [[First Information Report|FIR]] was filed against Nasrin in [[Bareilly]] by a cleric named Hasan Raza Khan, for hurting religious sentiments. Nasrin had allegedly tweeted on [[Twitter]] that "In India, criminals who issue [[fatwa]]s against women don't get punished." Raza Khan said that by accusing clerics of being criminals, Nasrin had hurt religious sentiments.<ref name=AntiFatwaTweet>{{cite news|title=Cleric files FIR against Taslima Nasreen's anti-fatwa tweet|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Cleric-files-FIR-against-Taslima-Nasreens-anti-fatwa-tweet/articleshow/26925330.cms|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=6 December 2013}}</ref>

On 2 July 2011, the house of U. Kalanathan, secretary of the [[Kerala Yukthivadi Sangham]], was attacked in [[Vallikunnu]] after he suggested on television that the temple treasures of [[Padmanabhaswamy Temple]] should be used for public welfare.<ref name=kalanathan>{{cite news|title=Rationalist leader's house attacked|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/rationalist-leaders-house-attacked/article2157439.ece|accessdate=23 October 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=4 July 2011}}</ref> On 20 August 2013, [[Narendra Dabholkar]], a rationalist and anti-superstition campaigner, was assassinated.<ref name=dabholkar/>

On 16 February 2015, rationalist [[Govind Pansare]] and his wife were attacked by unknown gunmen. He later died from the wounds on 20 February.<ref name=Pansare>{{cite news|title=Rationalist Pansare is dead|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/461081/rationalist-pansare-dead.html|accessdate=5 October 2015|work=[[Deccan Herald]]|date=21 February 2015}}</ref> On 30 August 2015, [[M. M. Kalburgi]], a scholar and rationalist, was shot dead at his home. He was known for his criticism of superstition and idol worship.<ref name=Kalburgi>{{cite news|title=Rationalist Kalburgi Shot Dead in Dharwad|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/Rationalist-Kalburgi-Shot-Dead-in-Dharwad/2015/08/31/article3002639.ece|accessdate=5 October 2015|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=31 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=Time-kalburgi>{{cite news|title=Indian Scholar Who Spoke Out Against Idol Worship Is Shot Dead|url=http://time.com/4016747/mm-kalburgi-india-murder-rationalist-idol-worship-hindu-nationalism/|accessdate=5 October 2015|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=31 August 2015}}</ref> Soon afterwards, another rationalist and author, [[K. S. Bhagwan]], received a threatening letter. He had offended religious groups by criticizing the [[Gita]].<ref name=BhagwanWriter>{{cite news|title=Writer Bhagwan receives threat letter|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/writer-bhagwan-receives-threat-letter/article7635331.ece|accessdate=5 October 2015|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=10 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=ThreatLetter>{{cite news|title=In Karnataka, Another Writer Gets Threat Letter After Scholar MM Kalburgi's Murder|url=http://www.ndtv.com/karnataka-news/after-mm-kalburgis-murder-writer-ks-bhagwan-receives-threat-letter-1215955|accessdate=5 October 2015|work=[[NDTV]]|date=10 September 2015}}</ref>

In March 2017, an Indian Muslim youth from Coimbatore, 31-year-old A Farooq, who became atheist, was killed by members of a Muslim radical group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/tamil-nadu-youth-h-farook-killed-for-being-an-atheist-father-says-he-too-will-become-one-4586999/|title=Tamil Nadu youth killed for being an atheist, father says he too will become one}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyo.in/politics/atheist-hacked-coimbatore-farooq-religion-god-conflict/story/1/16395.html|title=As long as gods are used for votes, Indian atheists will get killed}}</ref>

==Demographics==

===Indian government census===
The Indian census does not explicitly count atheists.<ref name="secularism">{{cite book|author=Phil Zuckerman|title=Atheism and Secularity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z1hbaAHsAlUC&pg=RA1-PA139|accessdate=7 September 2013|date=21 December 2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35182-2|chapter=Chapeter 7: Atheism and Secularity in India}}</ref> In the [[2011 Census of India]], the response form required the respondent to choose from six options under religion. The "Others" option was meant for minor or tribal religions as well as [[atheist]]s and [[agnostic]]s.<ref name=milliongods/>

The religion data from [[2011 Census of India]] was released in August 2015. It revealed that about 2,870,000 people had stated no religion in their response, about 0.27% of the nation's population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/753475/people-without-religion-have-risen-in-census-2011-but-atheists-have-nothing-to-cheer-about|title=People without religion have risen in Census 2011, but atheists have nothing to cheer about}}</ref> However, the number included atheists, rationalists and also those who believed in a higher power. [[K. Veeramani]], a [[Dravidar Kazhagam]] leader, said that it was the first time the number of non-religious people was recorded in the census. However, he added that he believed that the number of atheists in India was actually higher as many people don't reveal their atheism out of fear.<ref name=FirstTimeCensus>{{cite news|title=2.87 million Indians have no faith, census reveals for first time|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/2-87-million-Indians-have-no-faith-census-reveals-for-first-time/articleshow/48689278.cms|accessdate=10 September 2015|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=27 August 2015}}</ref>

===Different surveys===

====World Values Survey (2006)====

According to the 2006 [[World Values Survey]], conducted by the Dentsu Communication Institute Inc, Japan Research Center (2006), 6.6% of Indians stated that they had no religion.<ref name="dentsu">{{cite web|title=World Values Survey (2006) ''English source requested''|url=http://www2.ttcn.ne.jp/~honkawa/9460.html|accessdate=5 September 2013|language= Japanese}}</ref>

====WIN-Gallup Global Index of Religion and Atheism====

According to the 2005 Global Index of Religion and Atheism report from WIN-Gallup, 87% of Indians were religious and 4% called themselves atheists.<ref name=surveyTOI>{{cite news|title=More Indians have stopped believing in God: Survey|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-05-27/uk/39556084_1_more-indians-dip-4-people|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=27 May 2013}}</ref> According to the 2012 report by the same organisation, 81% of Indians were religious, 13% were not religious, 3% were convinced atheists and 3% were unsure or did not respond.<ref name=gallup2012>{{cite web|title=Global Index Of Religion And Atheism |url=http://redcresearch.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/RED-C-press-release-Religion-and-Atheism-25-7-12.pdf |publisher=WIN-Gallup |accessdate=3 September 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016062403/http://redcresearch.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/RED-C-press-release-Religion-and-Atheism-25-7-12.pdf |archivedate=16 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>

====Worldviews and Opinions of Scientists in India (2007)====

In 2007, a survey was conducted by the [[Institute for the Study of Secularism in Society and Culture]] of the [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] with the help of [[Center for Inquiry]] (India) called Worldviews and Opinions of Scientists in India. 1100 scientists surveyed from 130 institutes. Most of them identified themselves as [[secular]] (59%) or somewhat secular (16%) but refused to be labelled [[irreligious]]. 83% defined secularism, as it appears in the Indian constitutions, as the separation of state and religion. But, 93% also defined it as tolerance of other religious philosophies. 20% equated secularism to atheism. Only 11% called themselves completely not spiritual. However,  8% reportedly said they would refuse to do [[Stem cell controversy|stem cell research]] based on religious or moral convictions.<ref name=SecularScientists>{{cite news|title=Indian scientists are secular, but religious: Survey|url=http://computing.in.msn.com/article.aspx?cp-documentid=3207887|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=[[MSN]]|date=16 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006231549/http://computing.in.msn.com/article.aspx?cp-documentid=3207887|archivedate=6 October 2013}}</ref> [[Yagnaswami Sundara Rajan|Y. S. Rajan]] commented on this saying that most Indians don't feel there is a conflict between science and religion.<ref name=trinity>{{cite web|title=Worldviews and Opinions of Scientists India 2007-08|url=http://prog.trincoll.edu/ISSSC/INDIAN_SURVEY_WEBSITE/|publisher=[[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]]|accessdate=5 September 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006200643/http://prog.trincoll.edu/ISSSC/INDIAN_SURVEY_WEBSITE/|archivedate=6 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Other the hand, [[Innaiah Narisetti]], chairman of Center for Inquiry (India) and [[Pushpa Mittra Bhargava|Pushpa Bhargava]], the former director of the [[Centre for Cellular and Molecular Biology]], pointed out the lack of [[scientific temper]] among Indian scientists.<ref name=god_scientists>{{cite news|title=God save Indian science|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1080610/jsp/nation/story_9389713.jsp|accessdate=8 September 2013|newspaper=Telegraph India|date=10 June 2008}}</ref>

